{"id":"d=origam-topic-3665//p=fde58755bf9946fcaac37453859797db","tags":{"__document_id":["origam-topic-3665"],"__file_type":["text/plain"],"__file_id":["ead8838f0c534d8d8b1ab63d0ef8d03f"],"__file_part":["72d92efa5beb4e11b08955f743e9c0ab"],"__part_n":["1"],"__sect_n":["0"],"source":["origam-community"],"topicId":["3665"],"categoryId":["61"],"url":["https://community.origam.com/t/2-platform-overview/3665"],"title":["2. Platform overview"],"imagesFound":["4"],"imagesDescribed":["4"],"imageUrl":["https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/b/b177bb86dca0f276b05e1a87335176e7682f4b3c.jpeg","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/3/3cdc65e9373a963e3c0bbbecbe4a1fdf511ebaa9.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/b/b22dac5140bc1b0091e747e88408686289e85c1e.jpeg","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/c/c1c3d74886176bc233f81418d6f325174d927bc0.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":" client-facing interface is a single-page application ( SPA ). It primarily consists of a minimalist index.html file, a JavaScript file containing a lot of code, and a CSS file containing styles. \n   Containers \n To keep everything running smoothly, we recommend using  Docker containers . Containers allow you to run ORIGAM Architect, the server, and the database in isolated environments, making development and deployment more consistent and manageable. Whether you\u2019re working locally or in the cloud, containers provide flexibility and stability. \n Here\u2019s a simple diagram showing how the platform components and actors interact: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/3/3cdc65e9373a963e3c0bbbecbe4a1fdf511ebaa9.png]\nDescription: The diagram illustrates the architecture for an ORIGAM development and deployment environment, divided into three sections: Local Development, User Work, and Production Environment. In the Local Development section, GitHub is connected to ORIGAM Architect and ORIGAM Server, along with a Docker container that includes the Database Server and a Git repository. The User Work section features application end users accessing the ORIGAM frontend and a custom frontend via an API, with interfaces shown for both web browsers and mobile apps. The Production Environment section depicts a Backend server, which can be hosted on-premise or in the cloud, also utilizing Docker with the ORIGAM Server and Database Server.\n\n\n  \n \n   ORIGAM Project \n In ORIGAM, a  project  represents a specific application or information system within one environment. Each project consists of: \n \n  Model  \u2013 created in ORIGAM Architect and stored on disk. \n  Database  \u2013 running on a database server. \n  Server  \u2013 hosted in a Docker container. \n \n For best results, it\u2019s a good idea to have at least two environments: one for development and one for production. You may also want a third for testing, which mirrors your production environment. \n   Development Environment \n On your local workstation, your development environment includes: \n \n  Model  \u2013 created and edited in ORIGAM Architect. \n  Local database  \u2013 running in a Docker container. \n  Local development server  \u2013 also in a Docker container. \n  Local Git repository  \u2013 for version control. \n \n   Production Environment \n When you\u2019re ready to go live, your production environment includes: \n \n  Production database  \u2013 in a Docker container (either in the cloud or on-premises). \n  Production server  \u2013 in a Docker container. \n  Git hosting  \u2013 such as GitHub, GitLab, or Bitbucket. \n \n With everything set up, you\u2019re ready to create new systems or applications. That\u2019s where  ORIGAM Architect  comes in, so let\u2019s take a closer look. \n \n   ORIGAM Architect \n  ORIGAM Architect  is the integrated development environment (IDE) where you model your system. All the information is stored in XML files, and the server interprets this model to run your application. Using Architect, you can define: \n \n  Data  (your data model and relationships) \n  User interface  (how users interact with your app) \n  Business logic  (workflows, rules, and automation) \n  Integration  (APIs and connections to other systems) \n \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/b/b22dac5140bc1b0091e747e88408686289e85c1e.jpeg]\nDescription: The image displays a graphical user interface for a software application, specifically the \u0022BusinessPartner\u0022 data entity configuration screen. Key information includes: \n\n- **Info Section**: \n  - Id: 457a4391-e94f-424c-89d0-dc3804121ce6\n  - ItemType: DataEntity\n  - Package: AsapRoot\n  - SchemaItem: CZ.Advantages.Asap.Schema.EntityModel.TableMappingItem\n\n- **Schema Item Section**: \n  - Entity Name: BusinessPartner\n  - IsAuditingEnabled: True\n\n- **Mapping Section**: \n  - DatabaseObjectType: Table\n  - GenerateDeploymentScript: True\n  - MappedObjectName: BusinessPartner\n\n- **Misc Section**: DescribingField present.\n\nAt the lower part of the interface, the \u0022Find Results\u0022 section shows multiple entries, indicating a search or retrieval functionality linked to model elements such as page templates and data structures. The right pane of the interface, titled \u0022Model Browser,\u0022 includes folders for Common, Data, User Interface, and Business Logic components, further categorizing the software\u0027s functional areas.\n\n\n  \n   Data \n At the core of every app is its  data model . This is where you define the entities (objects) in your system, their attributes, and how they relate to each other. ","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-01T23:34:23"},"vector":[-0.020460121,-0.019800877,-0.060292345,-0.0052254926,-0.014389682,-0.0538115,-0.02354125,-0.007392954,0.0056048413,0.03957366,0.0014243781,0.01